  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited regulatory framework\n\n2. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed global standards for anti-money laundering (AML)\n- Created recommendations for national legal systems\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- US Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded investigative powers\n- Increased financial institution responsibilities\n\n4. Modern Developments\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased focus on digital currency transactions\n- Broader international cooperation\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Sophisticated transaction monitoring systems\n- Machine learning and AI in detecting suspicious activities\n- Real-time tracking of financial movements\n- Cross-border information sharing platforms\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced whistleblower protections\n- More aggressive enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislation continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques and technological innovations.",
